<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-12-21T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-12-21T03:00:00-05:00" n="503" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d503">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1115/2267: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-21T16:00:00+08:00">December 21, 1937—4
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received December 21—9:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1203. With reference to special train leaving December 23d, Japanese
                            Consul General informs me that details have been communicated to the
                            Japanese military and naval authorities in order that necessary
                            arrangements may be made “not to attack from the Japanese side, he said,
                            train with about 300 foreigners on board”.</p>
                        <p>Sent to Hankow, repeated to the Department.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>